FASHION
The wrap dress
Liana Satenstein visits Diane von Furstenberg=E2=80=99s archives, walking t=
hrough fashion history (and history history) in the process.
Diane von Furstenberg Wraps Me in a Wrap Dress, and Her Wisdom [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/49ffb69c-adc1-46f7-867f-3387cdd4b98f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ2=
9rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]
=E2=80=94Liana Satenstein  in Neverworns [ https://substack.com/redirect/d4=
f4aa32-3b85-48ee-9aa9-cf2b1da33cfd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjC=
wZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]
I pull up to DVF=E2=80=99s home and then enter. I=E2=80=99m not great at de=
scribing interiors, but there are a zillion books that seem to touch the he=
avens and a massive 12-foot antique desk. I spot a handful of massive Warho=
ls of von Furstenberg towards the ceiling. Diane comes up to me and offers =
me a coffee in that Belgian lilt, that jet-set Euro twang. I=E2=80=99m imme=
diately hypnotized. I remember my former Vogue colleague from 10 years ago =
describing the designer as foxy. Von Furstenberg is that indeed: catlike wi=
th a deep-set feline stare that tears into my soul.
I sit on a plush chair while five women on Diane=E2=80=99s team also sit ar=
ound us. Diane is curled up on the chair facing me, her legs tucked like a =
cat. She looks at me and says, =E2=80=9CSo, tell me your story.=E2=80=9D Su=
ddenly, I feel like I=E2=80=99m the only one in the room. That=E2=80=99s th=
e designer=E2=80=99s seduction.
She asks me about my upbringing. I tell her I was born and raised in a tiny=
 town in Massachusetts, and then she calls me a =E2=80=9Ccountry girl=E2=80=
=9D. Not totally: I share that I spent a zillion years in Crimea and Saint =
Petersburg, Russia. Then she asks me, with that searing stare: =E2=80=9CDid=
 you have an affair?=E2=80=9D I tell her about how I briefly dated a tax ev=
ader in Saint Petersburg, whom I met at Subway . . . the sandwich shop. =E2=
=80=9CI wish I had something more interesting to tell you!=E2=80=9D I say. =
But I don=E2=80=99t feel bad, nor am I embarrassed. Who can compete with DV=
F? Mick Jagger and David Bowie proposed a threesome to her back in the day.
Now for the motherlode. I=E2=80=99m in an adjacent warehouse to DVF=E2=80=
=99s home, which is a cornucopia of wrap dresses, all organized by year by =
her young archivist, Coco. This is the genesis of von Furstenberg=E2=80=99s=
 ferocious rise!
I strip in front of Diane, and she puts me into a verdant green jersey dres=
s in the =E2=80=9Ctwig print.=E2=80=9D This is one of her earliest pieces. =
The fabric is slinky and grippy, almost like a man=E2=80=99s hand is tender=
ly wrapped around my waist.
The dress, which is 50 years old, fits like a glove. I feel electric, like =
I have a slice of Diane=E2=80=99s =C3=BCber confidence; her =C3=BCber sensu=
ality coursing through me. =E2=80=9CI made the wrap dress, but the dress ma=
de me,=E2=80=9D she tells me, walking me through a zillion racks of archiva=
l pieces. The piece is a classic, maybe akin to a T-shirt or a suit jacket.=
 I love the way Diane wore her wrap dress in the =E2=80=9970s: that massive=
 collar, sassily flicked upward like a holier-than-thou royal.
